metadata.description:

This collection is intended to be customized and printed. Your initial thumbnail output is only the beginning â€” several parameters are changeable to find a combination and format to your liking. Please use the keys below to explore the thousands of possible variations within each piece.

metadata.name: Confini #46
metadata.description:
This is my last fxhash piece for a while, so that I can focus on my personal life. I tried to make a piece that creates the appearance of shapes scratched into the canvas. There are three carefully selected color palettes. One of them is heavily inspired by "Self-Portrait with Bandaged Ear and Pipe", by Van Gogh. These are heavily contrasting colors that I tried to get to work in coherence. One of the color palettes exists out of flavorful colors and means to spark joy in the viewer (depending on the outcome). The final color palette is one that is meant to evoke nothing but calmness. The colors are meant to remind of nature and serenity. I hope you enjoy my work.

Made in p5.js

By twistie

metadata.name: City of Harmony #13
metadata.description:
In the city of Harmony, all inhabitants lived with dignity and respect. They gathered to watch hot air balloons and ships, each carrying a unique dream, soar into the sky. The people worked together to support each other in making their dreams come true. The balloons and ships became symbols of unity and hope, and Harmony remained a shining example of what can be achieved through determination and perseverance.

- look for the gold mode
- hit 'p' for png export
- hit 's' for svg export

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #76
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press â€™sâ€™ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press â€˜pâ€™ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.name: Sixty# #126
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe thereâ€™s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press â€™sâ€™ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Trust #221
metadata.description:
Trust is an abstraction of the creative process, finding the line just before form becomes texture. Your experience with the painting requires trust; trust that something will appear from the chaos of the empty space, trust that the composition you imagine halfway through will evolve along with your ideas, and trust that the etchings lend a helping hand to the message of the piece. You may find yourself pulled left and right when decisions are made, and your interpretation at 25%, 50%, and 90% will all differ. This is what makes creating so fulfilling to me, a work of art can change course wildly from start to finish, ever molding itself until it enters the kiln.

Press â€˜1â€™, â€˜2â€™, or  â€˜3â€™ to increase resolution (default is 1, higher than default may not work on certain browsers. Successfully testing in Chrome, Brave, and Opera GX with hardware acceleration enabled)

Click or tap to zoom to full res (exact zoom depends on your display)

metadata.name: Knockout #70
metadata.description:
An exploration of screen printing techniques and how these effects can be achieved in generative work. The halftone effect works by placing very small dots next to each other to give the illusion of new shades and hues. Each Knockout samples three colors for the main composition and runs small sections of the canvas back through the machine after shuffling the base palette. The secondary passes vary in size, creating interesting emergent patterns on the overlap.

Press 's' in live view to save a .png

Built and tested with Chrome on Apple silicon. Some outputs may take up to 20s on slower machines.

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Forecast #42
metadata.description:
Looking forward. Looking back. Standing in one place. At some point I assume someone is going let me know the plan. One thing leads to another, everything is close and then distant. Kind of a mess to be honest. I'm trying to make it better, I'm trying to make something beautiful. If I can only make things okay. I just want everyone to have a nice time. Something must mean something. Look, here, that's the important bit, focus on that.

metadata.name: pen_tings #50
metadata.description:
A bit of scribbling, a bit of sketching. Experimenting with curves, colors and stop motion animation. Based on particle collision simulation. Inspired by ballpoint pen artworks and scribble drawings.

You can choose between two types of animation*:
- live drawing,
- animation of alternative versions (GIF generation).

Controls (in live view):
Press 's' to save a PNG image.
Press 'n' to generate an alternative version.
Press 'g' to generate a GIF (texture disabled).
Press 'G' to generate a GIF (texture enabled).
Press 'l' to enable live drawing animation.
Press '1-4' to render and save a PNG image (1: 2000x2000, 2: 4000x4000, 3: 6000x6000, 4: 8000x8000).
Pressing 'n', 'g', 'G', 'l', '1-4' reloads the page.

URL parameters (add to the URL in live view: &paramName=paramValue):
- mode - 0: image rendering (default: &mode=0), 1: live drawing animation, 2: GIF generation
- res - resolution; 1: 2000x2000 (default: &res=1), 2: 4000x4000, 3: 6000x6000, 4: 8000x8000; (to render and save a PNG image; only with: mode=0)
- tex - texture; 0: texture disabled, 1: texture enabled (default: &tex=1)
- alt - alternative version; 0: original version (default: &alt=0), [1, 255]: alternative version
- gres - GIF resolution; 1: 480x480, 2: 640x640, 3: 768x768, 4: 1080x1080 (default: &gres=4), 5: 1200x1200; (only with: mode=2)
- glen - GIF length in seconds; [1, 6], 2: 2 s (default: &glen=2); (only with: mode=2)
- gfps - GIF fps; 1: 5 fps, 2: 10 fps (default: &gfps=2); (only with: mode=2)

Image rendering (especially in high resolution) may take some time, please wait.
GIF generation (regardless of the selected resolution) may take several minutes, please be patient.
Chrome browser (desktop version) recommended.

-----
(*) WARNING: LIVE DRAWING ANIMATION AND GENERATED GIF (ESPECIALLY) CAN BE EPILEPTIC TRIGGERS. GIF GENERATION IS AN EXPERIMENTAL FEATURE.

Made with p5.js, matter.js (2D physicsÂ engine) and Trigfills (cross browser trigonometric functions consistency), see LICENSE.md.

varmaxart, February 2023
